Git commands cheat sheet

1. Command: git clone
  • When to use: To copy a repository from an existing source.
  • Parameters: Repository URL (and optionally a directory name).
    Example:
    o	git clone https://github.com/user/repository.git

2. Command: git branch
  • When to use: To create, list, or delete branches.
  • Parameters: -d (delete), -m (move/rename).
    Example:
    o	git branch feature-branch   # Create a new branch
    o	git branch -d feature-branch  # Delete a branch

3. Command: git reset
  •	When to use: To unstage changes or move the HEAD pointer.
  •	Parameters: --soft (move HEAD only), --hard (discard changes).
    Example:
    o	git reset --soft HEAD~1   # Undo the last commit and keep changes
    o	git reset --soft HEAD~1 # Undo the last commit and keep changes 

4. Command: git stash
  •	When to use: Temporarily save changes that you don't want to commit immediately.
  •	Parameters: -u (stash untracked files), pop (apply and remove latest stash).
  Example:
    o	git stash save "WIP: work in progress"   # Save changes to stash
    o	git stash pop    # Apply and remove the latest stash

5. Command: git bisect
  •	When to use: To perform binary search to find the commit that introduced a bug.
  •	Parameters: start (begin bisecting), good (mark a commit as good), bad (mark a commit as bad).
  Example:
    o	git bisect start
    o	git bisect good v2.0
    o	git bisect bad v2.5

